We’ve found fossilized transitional forms spanning across the record that gradually develop feathers, a lighter hollow skeleton for flight, and eventually losing all teeth around 80 million years ago. This tells us that birds began splitting off from reptile relatives during the time of the dinosaurs around 150 million years ago. So it makes perfect sense for modern birds to have traces of teeth in their genome. But if every animal was created at once by a god in its present form, why would birds have genes for teeth?


