Several years ago, scientists conducted an experiment where they placed cells from the mouth of a mouse embryo in the beak of a chick embryo. These cells combined and the mouse genes allowed the chick to form rudimentary teeth when it couldn’t before. This happened because over time, the chick’s DNA has lost the part of the genes that tells the cells to go make the teeth. Though the chick had genes for making the teeth from its reptilian ancestor, it needs help from the intact mouse go signal.

Through the lens of evolution, the presence of genes for reptilian teeth in birds makes complete sense, as birds developed from toothed reptilian ancestors.

We glanced into the genetic past of birds and we found that they retain the same genes their ancestors used to make teeth. So why don’t we see birds with teeth outside the window if they have the genes? Why still rudimentary teeth? 

If you visualize genes lined up along chromosomes like close neighbors living next door in a neighborhood, we find that in birds, the genes (or houses in this analogy) for making enamel are in the same ‘neighborhoods’ in reptiles and mammals. We looked for the enamel making genes in the chick DNA and the genes are still in their ‘neighborhood’ but badly mutated…

Visualize visiting an old neighborhood where several houses are broken down and have been abandoned for 80 million years! Who cares if you throw a brick through a window of a broken down abandoned house? Or 2? Well natural selection doesn’t care what you do with abandoned genes either! If there is a mutation in a gene that is not needed, it will be passed on because it doesn’t harm anything. Reproduction will continue to pass on old genes as they accumulate mutation, like an old house falling apart through time. These old genes will be useless just like the old houses, unless it can become renewed; which for a house could be a new tenant and a paint job, but for genes its mutation. Mutation will continue in the genes and sometimes (quite often actually) old useless genes gain a new function because of the right mutation. 

So if birds did not evolve from the reptilian-like ancestors we find in the fossil record, then why do birds have the ancient genes for their teeth?
