Someone got the idea to take the part of the eye that the blind cave fish was missing right before it broke down from the surface fish and plant it in the orbit. This lens from a surface fish, when placed in the eye of a developing blind cave fish, will cause the eye to continue developing and will grow into a functional eye. Blind cave fish have acquired changes in their genome that has caused eye cells to kill themselves at a certain stage. But when you give the blind cave fish a lens from a genome that doesn’t say “kill yourself,” the cells form the eye they originally inherited. 

Through the lens of evolution, this shows that the blind cave fish inherited functional eyes from its ancestors and over time have lost the need for sight due to the darkness in the cave system. The blind cavefish still have eyes and eye orbits that are functionless but are working together perfectly in the surface forms.

If blind albino cave fish were created to fit into their environment of darkness, why then does the fish still go through the development of the eye within an eye socket only to then break it down and cover it back up? What’s ‘intelligent’ about wasting that time and energy only to have the process cut short and reverse itself? 

The blind cave fish is one of many species of fish we know of that live in the darkness. Often these fish lose their pigments, change jaw formation, and develop odd sleep patterns. Although the blind cavefish and the surface dwelling Mexican tetra look different from one another, they can interbreed, and their offspring become hybrids that can also interbreed back with the parent populations. The two populations are genetically very similar, but cave fish have low genetic diversity from the constricted food. The intermixing of the cave and surface forms combine different traits of blind/albino/altered sleep cycles and differences in vision, color, and daylight, which causes the hybrids to have a wide range of color, eye size, visional capabilities, etc.

So the blind cave fish forms eyes but destroys them right afterward, and their same-species neighbors have fully functional eyes on the surface. This makes perfect sense when one understand evolution, but raises thousands of questions if Intelligent Design is to be taken seriously. 

